segments.text: And after you left St. Mary's, then what happened?
Well, that was in 31.
I came back here to A&M and finished up on my degree.
And I hadn't gotten my degree like I should have.
I went off.
I had a few hours, and I was a freshman coach with Roswell Higginbotham.

freshman coach and we had a very good team at the end so then I went back to San Antonio and after the finishing that year up I think that was 32 and the fall of 32 I helped coach and promoted games there in San Antonio and and then that in April
as a line coach, with the understanding that if he won, that I'd be here for, you know, the regular time.
I was, well, it wasn't an intern coach, I guess a seasonal coach, with the understanding that, see, he was on the spot then, although he had some pretty good seasons, so I was getting tired of him.
He hadn't won any championships, see?
Mm-hmm.
So I came back over here, we moved, my family came back over here, and I came over here in April for spring training.
And then I came back in mid-August for the varsity season.
And we had a good season.
We had 6-3-1.
Tied Texas on Kyle Field.
But that wasn't good enough for the farm students, so they just
they told Matty that he'd have to leave.
And that's when he went to SMU as assistant coach under Morrison.
What kind of coach was Matty Bell?
He was a good coach.
He was a good, sound, fundamental coach and a very likable man in the practice business.
He had a lot to do with, you might say, in my life because I did come back to A&M and got my degree.
And then I was
his assistant here, and what was going on.
We would have gone to North Carolina University, but if they hadn't fired Matty before the season was over.
But he was a very good coach, very good sound.
He was a whole lot like Mr. Bible.
Who replaced Matty Bell then?
Homer Norton.
Homer Norton came on.
Yeah, he came on.
And Norton tried to hire me back after I went.
Then I left here and went back to San Antonio to coach high school for a while.
What high school then?
At Black Ridge first as a track coach and a line coach, and then I went to Thomas Jefferson.
I had good success there.
I had boys like Kyle Roten.
Oh my, yes.
Dick McKissick and Weldon Humble and Charlie Parker.
I got into coaching track, and I made
probably the biggest success of my track coaching I did in my football.
I had a wonderful season over there.
Six seasons I played for the state champions against Odessa in 1946 in Austin and had one of the biggest crowds I ever had at a high school game.
There was a coach at SMU.
Hayden Frye.
Yeah, Hayden Frye was their quarterback.
How come you decided not to go to work for Homer Norton?
Was there any particular reason you didn't want to go back?
When I left here, A&M was good to me, and I didn't have really any animosity toward anybody.
But I knew that the coaching in colleges was so uncertain.
And in 1945, he asked me to come back over here as one of his assistants, but I declined, which was a good move.
And then Mr. Bell wanted me to go to SMU to be his line coach and track coach up there, and I declined that too.
He just figured that it was not enough job security.
That's right.
And I did have it in high school, although the salaries in those days that the coaches
So what I was making, so I was athletic director and head of football and track coach at Thomas Jefferson.
I won two state track championships there and I had some great sprinters for those days.
Charlie Parker, I don't remember, but they were boys could run nine, six, nine, seven, which was unheard of 30 years ago.
But, and then I was a very good friend of Harry Stadler's and Bill Carmichael.

And so after I turned down Mr. Norton's, didn't accept his position here at A&M, and then turned down Matty Bell's, well, Harry Stotley, who was a good friend of mine, we were friends in high school circles at that time, and Bill Carmichael was made athletic director after Norton left, and Stotley was made head football coach.
called me several times and wanted me to come back over here and I told them no.
I was well situated and they kept calling me and kept calling me and finally they caught me at a weak moment in which it was a good move for me.
Did you know Norton very well?
I knew him pretty well.
I did know him.
Mr. Norton, he made a wonderful record here.
But see, we weren't in the same circles at that time.
I was coaching in high school.
I knew him, but we did not on too personal.
You had no idea what kind of coach he was?
Well, the only thing I can say is he had the second best record they ever had at the end.
After Bibles, I guess Norton was the best.
But he was on his way out.
He hadn't won nothing.
They hadn't won a national championship in 39.
He was on his way out, too.
The only friend you have in coaching is the scoreboard.
At least in college.
The very guys that pat you on the back and glove you up while they're hiring you, they're the very ones that kick you out when you don't lose.
There's only one thing.
I hate to say it, but there's only one thing.
It's win and lose.
Losing, that's what.
Yeah.
Well, then you came here in what year?
And what was your position?
Freshman coach.
Freshman coach in 48.
I had a good freshman team.
How'd you all do that here?
We won them all except one game when they beat us, and they would beat us on a long pass.
We beat Texas and Bryce and TC and SMU.
Did you have any outstanding players on that team?
Yes.
Harry did a fine job in recruiting me.
Anytime a new coach comes in, he does a good job.
We had some boys like Littman, Bob Smith, Billy Tidwell, and the backfield, and a boy like Yale Larry.
I've got a picture of a bunch of those players back there.
We had a good, sound freshman team who later
And so how long was your freshman coach?
Well, in 48.
And then in July, 49, Carl Michael was then athletic director.
And he resigned to accept the superintendent.
Hey.
Hello.
This is my wife, Mrs. Chapman.
How are you?
Shall I bring you a cup of coffee or a Coke?
You want a Coke, a cup of coffee?
A cup of coffee would be very nice.
Sugar and cream?
Sugar and cream, please.
Yes, ma'am.
Thank you.
Okay, lost my train of thought.
You were talking about... Yeah, we were talking about you were a freshman coach in 48, and then you said you...
In July of 49, Mr. Carmichael, who was athletic director, resigned to become superintendent of the school in Bryan.
Why that ever chose me, I don't know, but I guess that made me athletic director.
It turned out to be a pretty good deal.
Yeah, that's right, a pretty good deal.
So you were athletic director then?
Well, I was athletic director from 48 or 49 up until Brian came here.
Then I was associate athletic director.
Could you tell us a little bit about this time until Brian got here?
The coaches you worked for, what was going on?
Well, at that time, when Stidler resigned, Mr. Gilchrist was president of the university at that time.
You see, I worked under some very, very conservative presidents.
What I mean by that, they said, you make it down there or else don't come up here asking us for any money.
You see what I mean?
Because they didn't have any money to give us because A&M in Texas had to, they were self-supporting.
We didn't get any appropriated funds from the state.
And well, when I took over the first thing,
wanted to do was to, we had a little old press box, you don't know, I haven't seen the picture.
Same pictures of it, yes sir.
The old press box and we didn't have any, we had an original stadium which was built in 27 and then I think finished in 29 and at that time when I took over we didn't have any money at all.
We just got through, Norton had done a good job with, with handling the money during his, because we had the big stadium
stadium debts still to be paid off.
And at one time, when I was back there, going back, re-enhancing back, I can remember in 33, the state didn't have any money.
I mean, the athletic department didn't have any money.
They'd give you a voucher.
And we had a very, very small budget to operate on.
Sorry, I ran a cream this morning.
All right.
And I took over where we just finished building the dressing rooms underneath the President's Stadium.
And I think we had $25,000 in the kitty, and we owed some money.
And like I said before, I have all the highest regard for all the presidents of A&M College.
they were conservative, they were minded people because they didn't have any money.
We hadn't hit the plateau of earnings coming in like we did there.
So the first thing I did was to enlarge
enlarged the stadium and put up a few.
You don't remember when we had 2,600 seats up there in the press box.
Well, this was the new addition that came up.
It was narrow.
That's right.
When was this built?
That was built in 1951.
I think 1951 or 1952 at the cost of $350,000.
How did you all raise the money for that?
Well, I pole barred it.
They said I couldn't do it.
I'm being a very pessimistic person anyhow.
I tried it, and we sold those options out at $50 apiece, I believe.
The records, I don't have them in the National Labor Department.
We raised about $100,000, and we had a little money.
I'd accumulated a little money.
Now, I've been known as pretty tight with athletic department money, but I wasn't tight with it.
Athletics is a business.
Of course, it's just a question of have- Either have it or don't have it.
Now, we had just as many scholarships.
We had just as many coaches.
Harry Stoddler had seven or eight coaches.
And we get past Harry's deal, and I'll get to others.
But you're asking about the finances.
And I borrowed $60,000 from a forum of students.
And they said, well, no, we don't want to let you.
We don't want you to get the money back or nothing.
So we hit it pretty lucky because we had a game with Michigan State that I'd gotten a hold of.
And a streak of luck hit us because it was a televised game.
Oh, I see.
And in those days, you didn't have to give your,
Southwest Conference, 80% of the money belonged to you.
And that was one reason why this rule went into effect.
I think we got about $89,000 out of the game, which was a lot of money in those days.
Certainly.
See?
And after we played the game and we'd gotten all this money counting, I think we got 120 counting the television rights, and Michigan State was a good gate.
why we had about $120,000.
Well, the conference then wanted some of that money.
We told them, well, there's nothing in your rules and regulations about it.
We'll divide it with you.
So the following year, they put in this regulation.
So I took that money and paid it.
In two years, the stadium was complete.
I think the press box costs $100,000.
And you mentioned the good gates.
When you're scheduling,
games in advance?
Did you all try to look for big draws?
Big draws.
And that's one of the things that the board of directors always jumped on me about.
You see, I had LSU, Michigan State, Michigan, Ohio State, schools like that.
We weren't drawing anything.
Big stadiums up there.
And they draw.
We weren't drawing for 15,000, 18,000 people here.
We had to do it.
We had to do it.
So those were real money makers.
Money makers in those days.
And even today, I started the series again with LSU back 10 years ago, 12, 15 years ago, way before I retired as athletic director.
You know what that game is bringing in and out?
Next year, $150,000.
Good, good.
That's marvelous.
Now, what...
The last three years that a contractor got with them, I was very much criticized by taking them because you ought to be playing them up here.
Well, LSU wouldn't come up here.
They play seven games a year.
You know what that's going to mean to us?
That contract expires in 75 next year.
It means that you've got to supplant that with another game about 50,000.
And athletic department now... Mm-hmm.
It had been subsidized by the Aggie Club.
We didn't have the Aggie Club.
I organized the Aggie Club in 1950.
You did.
How'd that come about?
How'd you decide?
Well, they said they couldn't do that.
Well, I paid off my debt there, and we scrounged around and got these good football games.
Texas had a longhorn club, and SMU had the Mustang club, and TCU had the hard and foggy club.
So I organized that, which they said we couldn't do.
But it didn't amount to too much during those days.
But it was the foundation and the organization of it that finally now is without it, we couldn't operate.
That was, I think, organized in 52.
Well, what you're saying then is you really don't make enough off the gates to run your athletic facility.
No.
We did it then, those days, by careful managing of our money.
But still, we had everything that the other teams had, too.
Could you run through some expenses as to where the money goes?
In other words, what salaries for coaches?
Now?
Yeah, what...
You mean now?
What you have to pay out.
Next year, I understand, the budget's going to be $1,500,000.
Mm-hmm.
Of that amount, now, I haven't got an idea of the budget.
I mean, I haven't seen it, but I imagine close to $500,000 would be the salary.
Mm-hmm.
That's really something.
Or if you take the scholarships, it would be 200 scholarships, say, at $1,500.
That's how much more.
Mm-hmm.
See, like that.
Then you're traveling, I don't know.
And of course, football really has to carry the load for all the others, too.
That's right.
That's right.
One question that bugs me, does basketball make enough?
No, it doesn't make them enough.
It won't, because I don't know what the budget for basketball is.
I did have a budget here.
I imagine the budget for basketball, I mean, don't take this as accurate because I don't know.
I could get it for you if you wanted.
No, I was just curious to know.
I imagine basketball runs around $100,000.
I just wondered if they made enough off of basketball maybe to break even.
No.
And of course, track makes almost nothing.
Nothing, and baseball makes nothing.
Nearly nothing.
Swimming and golf and tennis, they don't make nothing.
But the whole thing is made to the idea of carrying on a complete athletic program.
star, well, of course, it makes some money.
But you see, besides that money, we get a lot of money from the conference every year.
From the television?
Television.
You see, all the television money of all the teams in the Cotton Bowl money and all that goes into the pot.
You see?
And I think the department got over $120,000 this year from the proceeds from the conference.
Well, that certainly helps.
It helps, yeah.
Well, I noticed this next year we have a nationally televised game with the University of Texas.
Nationally televised?
Yes, sir.
Well, I might explain to you that.
80% goes to Southwest Conference.
That's this kitty we have.
And then it used to be 4% goes to NCAA.
That's 84%.
And then the two competing teams divide.
Split a little bit.
Yeah, 16% of it.
And if it's a national televised game, of course, it's worth a lot more.
I think $300,000, I guess, over the round, $300,000.
Just on the television.
I used to know exactly the amount.
Well, yeah, I understand that.
Well, now, we were talking about the early days.
We were up to about 1950, 51, and the additions to the stadium.
Yeah.
Can you tell us a little more what went on then in succeeding years and what some of your accomplishments, problems, frustrations maybe are?
Well, Mr. Stiler resigned, and then I was confronted with hiring a new football coach.
You were?
Yeah.
I was still athletic director.
And I suppose people put pressure on you then.
Well, it wasn't so much pressure, but it was the amount of money that the administration told me I could pay one.
Oh, I see.
What did they pay a football coach in those days?
I think Stiler was getting $8,500, $10,000.
Of course, that wasn't bad.
No.
But I went, the administration said, now you can hire a football coach, but he can't be over $3,500.
He can't be for one year.
How come one year?
Well, the Norton deal, you know, they paid out home of Norton, you know, and the administration had gone from one extreme to the other.
They had to buy Norton's contract.
That's right.
They bought his contract.
Which was only fair.
That's right.
That's right.
But now I had a frustration because I had some fine coaches that I had interviewed.
And when I told them what the proposition was, they laughed at me.
I'm not surprised.
I said, what's the matter?
Are you crazy?
They didn't tell me that in words, but I surmised that.
So I didn't know what to do.
So Mr. Williams, who was the athletic council member at that time,
came to me and said, now, you've got to get a coach here and get it soon, or else you're going to have to take it.
So I'd been through this long.
I said, well, I don't want to stay at College Station one or two years.
I do want to stay here a little longer.
So I went to Harry Stidler, who was a good friend of mine, and asked him who would he recommend on the staff that could fill the shoes of the head coach.
And he said, well, Ray George, who
had a fine background.
He was a USC football player, played professional football, and he coached at USC.
And he was hired to start as a line coach.
So we hired Ray, I think, at 8,000 a year.
Well, he was a fine gentleman.
And he was best liked football coach, I believe, as far as the former students were concerned.
I've heard this.
Anybody we had here.
But he wasn't a coach.
Maybe he wasn't a head coach.
He wasn't a head coach, that's it.
So Ray didn't have such bad.
Now we come up to this 1950.
Let's see, Harry quit in 49, 50, 51.
It's 51 team which should have won the conference.
That was Steitler's team, wasn't it?
Yeah.
And then he quit in 51.
He quit in 50 and 51.
Then Ray George for a year.
Oh, it's not important, we can, that's...
It's 51, 52, 53, and then Brian came in 54.
Ray was a fine gentleman, but he just wasn't a head coach.
The head coach nowadays, you just can't go out and pick up a guy and coach the ends over here for some school.

He has to know the entire functions of a football team, which includes the offense, the defense, the linebacker, the end play, the quarterback play, the halfback play, tackle play, defense, secondary defense.
He has to have a complete vision.
If he doesn't, he has to hire somebody that does know it and he don't know whether he knows it or not.
So there you are.
You're in a quandary.
But
Ray did fine, but then he didn't have a very good season, so Ray finally, he was a nice gentleman, a coach.
He was nothing wrong with Ray at all, but they disposed of him, asked him to resign, which he did, and that was a manhunt for the next coach.
Where did Ray George go then?
Do you remember where he went?
He went to work for Mr. Dunn.
Harold Dunn.
J. Harold Dunn?
J. Harold Dunn, who at that time was with the Shamrock Oil Company.
And Ray, he hired him on some building of some apartment complexes.
But of course, Ray didn't know anything about that.
I think it was just a nice way of getting rid of him.
Maybe so.
And he quit and finally went back to USC, where
I've lost track of him.
He's probably out in California.
Yes, he's in California.
Okay, then we get up to the search for the coach after he left.
How did that search go?
Well, I was sort of on the spot back in 54.
I'd been here, I'd be 48, 49, 51, 52, 53.
Five years as athletic director and they actually just didn't think that I was very progressive.
So I was given the task of getting a new head football coach.
So we went to Cincinnati, Ohio.
At that time, a fellow by the name of Mr. Penberthy was the chairman of athletic council.
And we went up there, and we interviewed all whole unforgotten.
Jim Myers was one who later came here.
And this guy coaches the Rams out there.
What was his name?
He's now coaching the San Diego Chargers.
I should know, but I can't think of his name.
I know his name as well as I do my own, but I can't think of it.
And we interviewed a lot of talent.
This guy that's now, Devine, who's coaching pro football, we interviewed him.
We practically hired him.
But then, of course, the boys' directors got into the picture.
And finally, I interviewed Coach Bryant.
And he was where, Kentucky then?
I interviewed him in Cincinnati.
And I told him, I said, Coach Bryant, I said, I don't have any, can't give you any amount of money we can give you, but I said, we'd like for you to come there.
And I said, you can have a head coaching job in the athletic directorial too.
I said, as far as I'm concerned, because I know I'm on the way out, but I couldn't make any kind of a deal.
I came on back and by that time, LSU was trying to hire him.
But anyhow, they got in touch with him, some of these foreign students or exes got in touch with him and they finally persuaded him to come.
So one day I was trying to hire him and about a week, 10 days later, he was hiring me.
So he had to rehire you then.
That's right.
And what was your position under Brian?
I was associate assistant athletic director.
Which probably means you did all the work for the office and he had the title.
Understand he came here also with a contract that he got a certain percentage of the gate.
Well, we'll get to that later on.
He's, I call him the man of destiny.
I don't care where you go, everything you did, you've seen people like that.
Why in the devil can't I do that?
He does it.
What do you call that?
Charisma?
Charisma or something.
Well, of course, you're familiar with when he came here and when he took his team out to Junction.
You know all about that.
I've been out there.
It's a rough place.
But he did well.
Coach Brian did well.
And this percentage deal I'll get on to later, but the first year, he didn't win but one game, if you look at the records.
I understand that.
The second year, he did a little better.
And the third and fourth year, he won the conference one year.
But of course, he was on probation.
And of course, he couldn't participate.
What really got us on probation without nailing down any names or anything?
You going to put that in the case?
You don't have to put any names in with it.
Well, there's a couple of cases.
One case was they tried to prove one of the stars that made Bryant a great coach proved that he was bought or given more than he's supposed to have been given.
And then secondly was they found out
player from South Texas was given a certain amount of, proved that.
That he was given certain things that were not conforming to him with the conference rules.
I see.
Do you think Bryant knew about this, or?
Oh, he knew about it just like Nixon knows about Watergate.
I see.
I see.
You can assume that.
I heard a story that he didn't even know that he was going to be put on probation until he went up to a conference meeting and was playing poker with some... No, I knew about it in Waco.
Of course, Waco, they announced it when we had the conference meeting up there.
They announced it after the fact of the meeting that they were put on probation.
But I knew it before that he did, actually.
I heard a story.
I don't know if it's true that he found out one night playing poker with Jess Neely and some of the rest of them.
No, I...
Maybe you're correct, but of course my only annoying about it was after the conference meeting.
I think it was held in Wakefield.
Well, how was Brian's brain here?
Did he rule with an iron hand?
Yes, he was, he was, his players, he ruled with an idea of fear.
Players liked him after he got out, but they thought he was a
while he was here.
He was fair.
He demanded 100% from his players.
As far as I'm concerned, my relations with him were 100% good because he was tight with the money, with the department's money.
He would shake down some of these exes, I guess.
That's what they say.
I don't know.
He'd shake them down.
We accumulated some money while he was here and built Henderson Hall.
Of course, you had a
With winning seasons, don't you make more money when you've got a winning season?
Yeah, but there again, we hadn't gotten to the plateau where A&M was really growing like the next year.
They ought to have some good crowds out there next year.
Well, we hope so.
But it was improving, I'd say, tremendously.
Yeah, from the first year where you win one and a little better.
So that by 56 and 57, he should have been drawing.
Well, he was drawing good, and we were making money.
We were making money.
Had some television games, probably.
Television games.
We were making money.
When we left here, we had some surplus.
In fact, in 57, you did get one bowl game, I believe, with Tennessee.
Went to Tennessee, and they beat us three to nothing.
I've forgotten what we got out of it, 60, 75.
Of course, any time you can play an extra game, that's a little more money, too.
Well, not altogether, because when last year I was here in 67, we played the Cotton Bowl and lost money.
You did?
Yeah.
How did you lose money on that?
That's interesting.
Gene Stallings just spent money like a wild man.
Oh, my.
I would have thought that you would have.
You see, the things have changed.
They divided the conference surplus up differently.
In other words, I think you would give so much per mile plus $60,000.
So you can spend $60,000 pretty quick if you're going to watch yourself.
You say spend money.
This was mainly on the team and their housing and food.
Invited everybody in the country to come up there on expense.
Well, it had been a long time since that had ever happened.
That's right.
Everybody went crazy.
It was first class.
It was first class.
I have no qualms about that, because I was getting ready to retire.
I didn't care.
Actually, I did care, but it wasn't the sore spot of mine.
You know, there's three types of people.
There's a type of person that's tight with his own money, and they spend everybody else's money.
Is that right?
Yes.
And there's a type of guy that's tight with his own money and tight with everybody else's money.
And there's a type of person that spends his own money and tight with... You see, out there, when I was there, I figured that that was more or less a...
I had to... That was a state institution.
I had to...
It was a sort of a... A public trust.
A public trust is what I thought.
But you couldn't tell these exes that.
Especially some of the more successful ones.
That's right.
Well, why did Bryant leave?
Was it more money?
Well, he told me confidentially that you couldn't win at A&M.
And I agreed with him.
I mean, consistently.
Now, get me wrong.
Could you explain that?
You mean you could maybe have one good season and then... Well, if you look at our records, we have one good season about every 13 years, and then we're at the bottom of the heap, the rest of them.
Now, why?
Well...
I'm not against A&M.
I'm an Aggie getting around.
Yeah, I agree.
I just think that maybe if we knew why, I could get a lot of money over there.
Well, I'll tell you why Bryant said it was hard to recruit.
Well, it was an all-military school.
An all-military school.
Second, we didn't have girls.
Right.
And thirdly, it was how we were situated.
gets on the nerves of all the rest of these schools.
Why?
Because they're jealous of us of what it is?
I don't know.
I think there's a certain percentage of that.
See, jealousy.
And because we have a rich heritage and have so many things that we are proud of.
I think maybe they don't like us because we're probably just a little bit clannish.
Yeah.
We stick together.
Stick together and clannish.
And we have a rich heritage.
And we have a great spirit.
And no other school has, I don't imagine.
Even the armed service schools, Army and West Point Navy, have us closely knitted together.
They have a rich tradition.
But this is why he said he left, really.
It's because you couldn't leave.
One reason, I think, and the second reason was the fact that he wanted to go back to Alabama, which he thought would be a better all-around position than the one at the A&M that he could accomplish
being the only school in Alabama except Auburn.

You see, if you stop and visualize this thing, and I've always said this, and it's not to say anything against schools that are land-grant schools, but how many land-grant schools have great football teams?
Can you answer that question?
It's sporadic.
They'll come up one year.
Purdue comes up one year.
And then this doubt drops down.
But now how many schools like Ohio State and USC?
Well, Ohio State's a land-grant school.
Yeah, it's about the only one that you might say.
But it was made the major university.
That's right.
It's the university first.
And then the agriculture, it seemed like LSU, it's a land-grant school.
But it's the only one.
But it's the only university, see.
I see what you mean.
